Murder Accountability Project¶

The Murder Accountability Project (MAP) is a nonprofit organisation publishing data on solved and unsolved homicides in the United States. The information is acquired from federal, state and local governments and includes murders from the FBI's Supplementary Homicide Report as well as more than 33,000 homicides obtained through the Freedom of Information Act for homicides not reported to the Justice Department.

The information gathered by MAP is the most complete data on U.S. homicides available anywhere.

There are two datasets:

  • Uniform Crime Report UCR (from 1965 onwards)
  • Supplementary Homicide Report SHR (from 1976 onwards)

The UCR summarises all homicides and homicide clearances reported from 1965 to the present, making it the ideal dataset to study clearance rates.

The SHR dataset includes the age, race, sex and ethnicity of victims as well as the weapon used and the circumstances surrounding the killing. Names are not reported, but the month, year, victim's demographic characteristics and the reporting agency are included. Police also report demographic information about offenders when the killer has been arrested, however, reports are rarely updated which means this information might be missing where arrests were made after the SHR was filed. It is also for this reason that the SHR is not a reliable source when studying clearance rates - between 5 and 10 percent of homicides noted as unsolved at the time of reporting to the SHR were solved later.

In [6]:
# helper function for visualising homicide clearance
def plot_homicide_clearance(grouped_data, chart_title):
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

    labels = grouped_data.index

    ax.bar(labels, grouped_data["MRD"], label="MRD")
    ax.bar(labels, grouped_data["CLR"], label="CLR")

    ax.set_title(chart_title)
    ax.legend()

    plt.show()
In [7]:
plot_homicide_clearance(group_sums, "Uniform Crime Report for Homicides: 1965-2020")

The total height of the bars in above bar chart (blue and orange parts combined) shows us the total number of murders reported in a particular year. The orange portion represents the homicides that were cleared, and the blue zone - the difference between total and solved murders - highlights the number of homicides per year that went unsolved.

In [8]:

total_cleared = sum(ucr["CLR"])
percentage_cleared = round(total_cleared / total_murders * 100, 2)

of all reported homicides from 1965 to 2020 - remain unsolved.")

In this blog post, MAP share that they believe the decline in clearance rates is caused by a failure to give necessary resources to local police as well as a failure of political leaders to make solving homicides a priority.

Exploring the Data¶

Relationship¶

The most common relationship value in our data is "relationship not determined" - where we do know the relationship, murderers are most commonly acquaintances, strangers, or persons otherwise known to the victim.

These groups account for 637614 murders in total - 77.29% of murders in our data.

It is important to note that the Relationship column describes the relationship between offender and victim from the offender's point of view - if a husband murdered his wife for instance, the relationship as per our data is "Wife".

In other words, the Relationship column can be thought to describe who the victim was.

We will plot a pie chart to visualise who most commonly falls victim to offenders they have a somewhat close relationship with.

To make the pie chart more readable, let's first combine victim groups with less than 5000 homicides per group together into one.

In [29]:
relationship_vc_series = shr["Relationship"].value_counts()[4:]  # isolating the remaining relationships of interest
count = 0
relationships_list = []

for i in range(0, len(relationship_vc_series)):
    if relationship_vc_series[i] < 5000:
        count += relationship_vc_series[i]
        relationships_list.append(relationship_vc_series.index[i])

print(relationships_list)
print(count)

relationship_vc_series.plot.pie(label="", autopct='%.2f')
Out[31]:
<AxesSubplot:>

A few interesting findings:

  • Wives, friends, girlfriends and sons most commonly fall victim to offenders they are close with, namely their husbands, friends, boyfriends or parents (mother or father). Together, they represent almost 50% of close-relationship homicides.
  • Children are more often killed by their parents than parents are killed by their children.
  • Women are more often killed by their partners than men.

Before we move on, let's quickly check whether our data confirms the common believe that most murders are committed by offenders known to the victim.

In [32]:

homicides_to_consider

In [34]:
print(f"Out of the {homicides_to_consider} homicides with established relationship between offender and victim, \
{murdered_by_stranger} murders representing {murdered_by_stranger_percent}% were committed by strangers. This means that \
the grand majority of homicides ({round(100-murdered_by_stranger_percent, 2)}%) were indeed committed by offenders \
to some extent known to the victim.")

Out of the 505345 homicides with established relationship between offender and victim, 121483 murders representing 24.04% were committed by strangers. This means that the grand majority of homicides (75.96%) were indeed committed by offenders to some extent known to the victim.

def style_function(feature):
    state = state_murders_dict.get(feature['properties']['name'])
    return {'fillColor': '#gray' if state is None else colormap(state),
            'fillOpacity': 0.6,
            'weight': 0.2}

# helper function to display dataframes side by side
from IPython.display import display_html

def display_side_by_side(*args, titles):
    html_str = ""
    for df, title in zip(args, titles):
        html_str += '<th>' + f'<h3>{title}</h3>' + df.to_html() + '</th>'
    display_html(html_str, raw=True)

Looking at the State, Month, Weapon, Relationship and Circumstance columns, the patterns in our data don't appear to have changed from previous years - the 2020 numbers are just higher.

Looking at patterns, we again find that the 2020 data is very similar to the details reported for previous years. It turns out that identifying the change in murder rate is easy compared to figuring out why the increase occurred. We might have to look beyond our data for further insights.

Additional research using the MAP website and other news articles online (i.e. this "The Intercept" article) suggests that there were a number of contributing factors that led to the big 2020 murder spike. The most important are believed to be the Covid-19 pandemic, the public outrage over the murder of George Floyd and widespread demonstrations on behalf of the Black Lives Matter movement, and a sudden influx in firearms followed by a higher percentage of crimes being committed with guns, causing more deaths.

To tie this back to our earlier findings - the 2020 spike in homicides and low in murder clearance rates are likely interrelated, as one can imagine the nation's understaffed police and sheriff's departments struggling to keep up with the unusually high number of murders needing to be investigated, while also having to deal with the pandemic and the changes to the public's perception of police legitimacy.
